<tr><td align="left" valign="bottom" width="98%"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/toptab.gif" width="98" height="10" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0"></td><td align="left" valign="bottom" width="22">&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td bgcolor="#3F403F" width="98%" class="cheader"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></td><td bgcolor="3F403F" valign="top" align="right" width="22"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/topcorner.gif" width="23" height="22" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="right"></td></tr>
<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> Control Your Destiny: Card Advantage<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/swtcg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/swtcg/main/mpage.php?member=10789'>Chris "McLarenC" McLaren</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/swtcg/main/mpage.php?member=10789&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 28, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> 	In the last article I talked about manipulating build points, now I will look at cards that allow you to cycle through your deck quicker or to retrieve discarded cards, thus achieving a card advantage.  Card advantage can be a big deal in most any game.  These cards are the ones that will help you to achieve this.  And now a look at the various cards:<br>
<br>
	Dark Side Character:<br>
Shu Mai {A} (45,U,3,30,3,2): Draw a card then discard a card<br>
Infantry Battle Droid, B1 Series  (88,U,2,40,2,1): Draw a card when this is discarded<br>
<br>
	Dark Side Ground:<br>
Tyranus&#39;s Geonosian Speeder {A} (52,R,6,40,2,1): Search your deck and place a battle card into your hand<br>
Reek  (102,U,3,50,2,2): Draw a card, discard a card<br>
<br>
	Dark Side Space:<br>
Trade Federation C-9979  (112,U,4,20,2,5): Draw a card<br>
<br>
	Dark Side Mission:<br>
Plot the Secession  (38,R,3): Discard your hand and draw 5 cards<br>
Splinter the Republic  (107,U,1): Search your deck for a copy of any card in an arena <br>
<br>
	Light Side Character:<br>
C-3PO {A} (67,U,3,10,1,3): Discard 2 Cards, Draw 2 cards<br>
<br>
	Light Side Ground:<br>
Jedi Patrol  (91,U,3,30,3,3): Draw a card, discard a card<br>
<br>
	Light Side Space:<br>
Corellian Star Shuttle  (129,C,4,20,3,4): Draw a card<br>
<br>
	Light Side Mission:<br>
Jedi Council Summons  (25,R,2): +1 force and take and Jedi card into your hand<br>
Wedding of Destiny  (118,U,2): Draw 3 cards and gain a force<br>
Jedi Call for Help  (24,R,3): If you have a Jedi in the Character Arena, search your deck for any unit and place it into your hand<br>
<br>
	Neutral Ground:<br>
Jawa Sandcrawler  (90,U,4,10,2,7): Draw 2 cards, discard 2 cards<br>
<br>
	Neutral Space:<br>
Coruscant Freighter AA-9 {A} (77,U,7,20,1,8): Draw 3 cards discard 2<br>
<br>
	Neutral Mission:<br>
Ship Arrival  (106,U,2): Reveal cards until you get one from your choice of arenas, place it in your hand<br>
Hatch a Clone  (141,C,1): Return up to 2 ground units from the discard pile to your hand<br>
Take the Initiative  (174,C,1): Return up to 2 space units from the discard pile to your hand<br>
<br>
	Now this is quite the list.  There are a total of 18 cards, or 10% of the set that allow you some sort of card advantage.  Now I will quickly split them up into types of cards, and opine on their use.<br>
	First there are the cards that allow you to retrieve cards from the discard pile.  Right now they are “Hatch A Clone” and “Take the Initiative,” the difference being one retrieves ground units and the other retrieves space units.  These cards are great for decks with low build cost units.  Thus when they are destroyed they can be retrieved and redeployed.<br>
	Next you have the cards that allow you to draw cards and discard cards.  Shu Mai, Reek, Jedi Patrol, and Jawa Sandcrawler all allow you to draw a number of cards and then discard the same number.  C-3PO works in the opposite way, with the cards being discarded and then drawn.  The Coruscant Freighter AA-9 draws 3 cards and then discards 2, giving you one extra card.  The C-9979 and Corellian Shuttle allow the you to draw a card.  The Infantry Battle Droid allows you to draw a card when it is discarded.  Each of these abilities allows you to get through your deck quicker and to see more of your cards. <br>
	The dark side has the mission card “Splinter the Republic” and the light side has “Jedi Call for Help” each of which allow you to select a given card and place it into your hand.  “Jedi Council Summons” does the same, but allows you to draw a specific Jedi card into your hand.    Tyranus’ Speeder allows you to place a battle card into your hand.  “Ship Arrival” allows you to select a specific arena and reveal cards until a unit from that arena is revealed and then place it into your hand.   Each of these cards allows you to have some control over what unit you are going to be added to you hand.  These cards are also useful when attempting to completing stacks.<br>
	But I have saved the ultimate card advantage card for last, “Wedding of Destiny.”  It allows you to add 3 cards to your hand and as an added bonus you get an extra force.  Any light side deck can benefit from these advantages.  There are no disadvantages from adding cards to your hand and the additional force can be used to help defend against attack or to use other battle cards.  It is probably one of the best cards in the game.<br>
	Once again, this strategy does not yield itself to a specific type of deck.  Rather it probably yields itself, at least in part, to almost any deck design.  As stated above, any light side deck can benefit from the addition of wedding of destiny.  Also swarm decks are benefited by faster cycling of cards through your hand.  Decks that depend on stacking can definitely use the ability to pull specific cards from the deck.  Now another combination is to us “Departure Time” along with the “Battle Droid” to not only gain an additional card, but also build points.<br>
